        <div type="letter">
            <div type="text">
                <opener>
                    <placeName><hi rend="print">Down, | Beckenham, Kent.</hi></placeName>
                    <date>Nov. 13<hi rend="superscript">th</hi></date>
                    <salute>My dear M<hi rend="superscript">r</hi> Trimen</salute>
                </opener>
                <div type="transcription">
                     
<p>I write one line to say how sorry I am not to see you before your return to the Cape, which I presume will be soon. But I cannot get my head steady enough to see anyone. I have just returned from a visit to my sister for a week, but I was forced to spend nearly all the day in my bed-room.—<ref target="#foot.f2"/></p>
<p>I read with much interest some little time ago your paper on geographical Distribution of Beetles; &amp; agreed, I believe, with all your general remarks.—<ref target="#foot.f3"/></p>
<p>I wish you all success in your future researches &amp; remain | Yours very sincerely | Ch. Darwin</p>
<p>If on the point of starting do not trouble yourself to answer this.—</p> 
                </div>
            </div>
            <div type="tnotes">
                <note xml:id="tnote.n1">, I believe,] <hi rend="italic">interl</hi> </note>
            </div>

            
            
            
            
        </div>

        

        

        <div type="footnotes">
            <note xml:id="foot.f1">The year is established by the reference to Trimen 1871 and by CD’s stay at Leith Hill Place (see nn. 2 and 3, below).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f2">CD visited his sister, Caroline Susan Wedgwood, at Leith Hill Place in Surrey, from 3 to 10 November 1871 (CD’s ‘Journal’ (Appendix II). CD had been unable to receive a visit from Trimen in August, while CD was staying in Albury, Surrey (<ref target="./DCP-LETT-7916.xml" resp="#mjhawkins">letter from Emma Darwin to Roland Trimen, [22 August 1871]</ref>).</note>
            <note xml:id="foot.f3">CD’s annotated copy of Trimen’s paper, ‘Notes on the geographical distribution and dispersion of insects’ (Trimen 1871), is in the collection of unbound journals in the Darwin Archive–CUL.</note>
        </div>        
            
